1 (d) to announce or follow a policy of denial or limitation of educational opportunities of a group or
2 its members, through a quota or otherwise, because of race, color, sex, marital status, age, creed, religion,
3 physical or mental disability, or national origin.
4 (2) For the purposes of this section, it is not an unlawful discriminatory practice for a student to:
5 (a) call another student by the student's legal name; or
6 (b) refer to another student by the student's sex.
7 (3) It is an unlawful discriminatory practice for an educational institution that operates, sponsors, or
8 facilitates athletic programs or activities to permit a person whose sex is male to participate in an athletic
9 program or activity that is designated for females.
10 (4) It is an unlawful discriminatory practice for an educational institution to fail to provide an
11 individual access to a restroom, locker room, shower area, or sleeping quarter that is not accessible by a
12 person of the opposite sex while in use by the individual.
13 (a) This subsection (4) does not apply to a person who enters a restroom, locker room, shower
14 area, or sleeping quarter designated for the opposite sex:
15 (i) for custodial or maintenance purposes;
16 (ii) to render medical assistance; or
17 (iii) during a natural disaster, emergency, or when necessary to prevent a serious threat to order or
18 safety.
19 (b) Nothing in this subsection (4) may be construed to prohibit an educational institution from:
20 (i) adopting policies necessary to accommodate persons protected under the Americans with
21 Disabilities Act of 1990, 42 U.S.C. 12101, et seq., young children in need of assistance, or elderly persons
22 requiring aid;
23 (ii) establishing single-occupancy or family restrooms, locker rooms, shower areas, or sleeping
24 quarters; or
25 (iii) redesignating a multi-occupancy restroom, locker room, shower area, or sleeping quarter from
26 a designation for exclusive use by one sex to a designation for exclusive use by the opposite sex."
